          "body": "Exodus 15:1-18 is widely regarded by scholars as one of the oldest pieces of Hebrew poetry in the canon, possibly preserving archaic linguistic features that predate the prose narrative of chapters 1-14. Its antiquity matters theologically: the song is not editorial gloss but the spontaneous liturgical response of eyewitnesses. It opens with a couplet that functions as both title and confession: 'I will sing to the LORD, for He is highly exalted; the horse and its rider He has hurled into the sea' (v. 1). The Hebrew *gaah* — highly exalted — carries the sense of rising in splendor, as a wave rises above the sea. The very medium of Israel's near-death has become the instrument of YHWH's glory. The song does not merely report what happened; it frames what happened inside the larger story of who YHWH is. By verse 3 the claim is made in its starkest form: 'The LORD is a warrior; the LORD is His name.' The two halves of the line must be held together. The warrior-identity is not autonomous militarism; it is the expression of the covenant name, YHWH — the self-existing God who binds Himself to His people."
