        "number": 4,
        "title": "Miriam and antiphonal response — worship as communal act",
        "range": "15:19-21",
        "excerpt": "Miriam the prophetess, Aaron's sister, took the timbrel in her hand, and all the women went out after her with timbrels and with dancing.",
        "body": "The prose narrator intervenes in verse 19 to re-anchor the song in history. The summary statement — horses, chariots, horsemen into the sea; Israel walked on dry ground — is not redundant. It functions as an editorial underscore: the poetry of vv. 1-18 is accurate history, not hagiographic exaggeration. Then verses 20-21 introduce the chapter's second voice: Miriam.\n\nMiriam is identified with two titles. *Neviah* — prophetess — is the first occurrence of this designation for a woman in the Bible. In the Old Testament, the female prophets are few and notable: Miriam (here), Deborah (Judges 4:4), Huldah (2 Kings 22:14), Noadiah (Nehemiah 6:14 — a false prophet), and Isaiah's wife (Isaiah 8:3). The title signals that Miriam's leadership at the sea is not informal exuberance but recognized prophetic office. 'Aaron's sister' places her within the prophetic-priestly leadership family that will govern Israel's cultic life throughout the wilderness period (cf. Numbers 12:1-2, where Miriam's prophetic standing is the basis of her claim to authority alongside Moses).\n\nHer act — taking the timbrel, leading the women in dance — is embodied liturgy. The Hebrew *mecholah* (dancing) is processional, communal dance, not performance. The women's worship is participatory: 'all the women went out after her.' The antiphonal refrain she leads (v. 21) reprises the opening couplet of Moses's song exactly. This is not coincidence; it is the technique of Hebrew responsive worship by which the congregation's voice answers the leader's proclamation, and the identical words anchor the theological content as the shared confession of the entire community, men and women together.\n\nHistorical-critical scholars have sometimes argued that Miriam's refrain (v. 21) is the original song and Moses's song (vv. 1-18) is an expansion. This view is speculative and has been persuasively challenged (see John Durham, Exodus, WBC, 1987). The canonical text presents Moses's song as primary and Miriam's refrain as the communal response — a liturgical structure that serves the theological claim: one man's witness becomes the whole people's confession.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Neviah* (prophetess) — the feminine form of *navi'*, prophet; one who speaks on behalf of God, not merely one who predicts the future. *Toph* (timbrel/tambourine) — frame drum, the standard instrument for women's victory celebrations in ancient Israel (cf. Judges 11:34; 1 Samuel 18:6). *Mecholah* (dancing) — processional dance in celebration; same root used in Psalm 149:3; 150:4."
